Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @potatoes{600%g} into 2cm chunks (peeling optional).

Pop the chunks onto a large (lined) #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn the tray halfway through.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Meanwhile, to make your slaw, halve the @cabbage{1}, cut out and discard the tough core, then thinly slice. Add to a #bowl{} and mix with half the @aioli{2%sachets}. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Mix the @miso paste{1%sachet} and remaining aioli in a #small bowl{}.

Trim and thinly slice the @scallion{2}.

Peel and grate the @ginger{1}. Use a #teaspoon{} to easily scrape away the peel.

Place a #pot{} over medium heat (without oil).

Once hot, dry-fry the @sesame seeds{1%sachet}, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove from the pot and set aside.

Return the pot to medium-high heat with @butter{to taste} and the @dried chilli flakes{2%sachets} (use less if you don't like spice).

Fry for ~{30%seconds} then remove the pot from the heat.

Add the @honey{2%sachets} and mix well to combine. Set aside and cover to keep warm.

Place a #pan{} over medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, fry the @Irish pork mince{240%g} until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks. Season with salt and pepper. IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw mince. Mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the ginger and fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Remove the pan from the heat and stir through the @hoisin sauce{2%sachets}.

Place the @bao buns{1%pack} on a #plate{} (three at a time) and microwave, covered, for ~{1%minute}.

Keep covered until ready to serve.

> TIP: You can also steam the bao. Place a large pot with 2cm of water over high heat. Once boiling, place a #colander{} lined with a #baking sheet{} on the pot. Place the bao (three at a time) on the baking sheet, cover and steam for 3-4 mins.

Once the potatoes are cooked, toss them through the hot honey and divide between plates.

Fill the bao buns with hoisin pork and a little slaw.

Drizzle the miso aioli over the top.

Serve with remaining slaw alongside.

Finish with a scattering of sliced scallion and sesame seeds.